\intbl \ql \b Background\b0 \line The Sherq Centre of Excellence \'28PTY\'29 LTD is not yet registered with the Department of Higher Education and Training as a private higher education institution and does not have any programmes accredited by the CHE.\line \line The Institution applied for accreditation of the Bachelor of Business Administration Financial Markets and Instruments which was tabled at the AC meeting held on the 10th of March 2020 and HEQC meeting held on the 7th of April 2020.\line \line The programme was not accredited for the following reasons\'3A\line 1. The relationship between the two centres\'2C i.e. The Facilitation Workshop and SHERQ Centre of Excellence\'2C is not clear. \line 2. There is discrepancy in the total number of credits for this programme. \line 3. The teaching and learning strategy is not clear and not aligned to the information provided in Criterion 1. \line 4. Although the Institution indicated the main campus at Diagonal Street as the only site of delivery\'2C the submission refers to other sites of delivery\'2C e.g. client sites. The Institution must provide information regarding all sites of delivery and confirm the mode of delivery.\line 5. The assessment strategy is vague. Assessment methods include structured activities\'2C questioning\'2C observation and documentation\'2C while the module descriptors mention examinations and a portfolio of evidence. \line 6. The Assessment Policy states that\'2C \'27In order for a candidate to be deemed competent they must meet the Specific Outcomes or Assessment Criteria of the relevant Unit Standards.\'27 Policies should be relevant to higher education programmes. \line 7. No enrolment numbers were provided\'2C and it was not possible to determine the infrastructural and resource needs. \line 8. The submission confirms that a library is available\'2C but no information pertaining to the library holdings\'2C any databases or online subscriptions was provided.\line 9. The qualification applicable to this submission is indicated as an NQF Level 7 qualification\'2C while the submission indicates that the SHERQ Centre of Excellence \'28Pty\'29 Ltd is able to provide learning solutions from NQF Level 1-6 with a specific focus on the financial services sector. It is not evident whether the Institution is able to offer NQF Level 7 qualifications.\line 10. The title of the programme is not aligned to the HEQSF. \line 11. The minimum duration for full-time study does not meet HEQSF requirements. \line 12. The reading list does not include complete information regarding author and title in all instances. Some of the resources are outdated. Furthermore\'2C some of the sources are not relevant to a qualification at Higher Education level. \line 13. The relevance of Work-Integrated Learning in this programme is not clear. No credits are awarded for WIL\'2C although substantial learning time is allocated to WIL \'28section 1.4\'29\'2C and assessment of WIL was described in section 1.10. Furthermore\'2C the duration of WIL is not clearly indicated. \line 14. The admission criteria in the HEQC submission and the SAQA application are not the same. Furthermore\'2C the Learner Admission and Support Policy refers to SETA-related qualifications. Admission requirements are not aligned to policy and legislation for Higher Education programmes.\line 15. No information is provided regarding enrolment planning. No enrolment numbers were provided.\line 16. The academic staff complement is not sufficient in size\'2C expertise or experience in the field to support a 360-credit Bachelor\'E2\'80\'99s Degree.\line \line The Institution submitted a representation which has been evaluated.\cell \pard 

